    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-04-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-04-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="475"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d475">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.8591/942</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Veracruz</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cochran</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 119</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Veracruz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-04-23">April 23,
                            1940</date>.<lb/>[Received April 25.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to despatch no. 97 from
                    this office, dated April 2, 1940,<note n="5" xml:id="d475fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> reporting that the German tanker <hi rend="italic">Tine
                        Asmussen</hi>, <pb facs="0424" n="412" xml:id="pg_412"/> which had been
                    anchored for some time in the bay of Coatzacoalcos, had been bought by
                    Mexico.</p>
                <p>The local daily newspaper, <hi rend="italic">El Dictamen</hi>, today carries a
                    short news item from Coatzacoalcos, dated April 22, reporting that the Mexican
                    flag was raised on the vessel at 3 o’clock that day and that it had been given
                    the name of <hi rend="italic">Juan Casiano</hi>. It is reported that the new
                    Mexican tanker is the largest of the ships belonging to Petroleos Mexicanos. It
                    is believed that the implications of this transfer of the title of a German ship
                    are well known to the Department.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William</hi> P. <hi rend="smallcaps">Cochran, Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
